\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 II. OVERTURNING THE PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION WILL INCREASE THE RISK OF UNCONSTITUTIONAL POLICING AND SUBJECT LATINOS TO RACIAL PROFILING AND OTHER CIVIL RIGHTS VIOLATIONS.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Prior experience teaches that it is often a "disastrous and expensive" mistake to involve local police in immigration enforcement because such efforts may foster widespread racial profiling and other civil rights violations. n31 Recent history provides significant  \b \i0 \ul0 [*19]\b0 \i0 \ul0   evidence why the Enjoined Provisions will lead to unconstitutional discrimination if they are implemented.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n31 Craig E. Ferrell, Jr., \b0 \i \ul0 Immigration Enforcement: Is It a Local Issue?,\b0 \i0 \ul0  71 The Police Chief (Feb. 2004); see also ACLU of North Carolina and UNC Chapel Hill Immigration & Human Rights Policy Clinic, \b0 \i \ul0 The Policies and Politics of Local Immigration Enforcement Laws - 287(g) Program in North Carolina\b0 \i0 \ul0  43-47 (2009), http://www.law.unc.edu/documents/clinicalprograms/287gpolicyreview.pdf; Trevor Gardner II & Aarti Kohli, \b0 \i \ul0 The\b0 \i0 \ul0  CAP. \b0 \i \ul0 Effect: Racial Profiling in the ICE Criminal Alien Program\b0 \i0 \ul0  4-5 (2009), http://www.law.berkeley.edu/files/policybrief_irving_FINAL.pdf (finding "compelling evidence" of "aggressive" racial profiling of Latinos by Irving, TX police officers after they began participating in the criminal alien program).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**34]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 If the Enjoined Provisions are allowed to take effect, Latinos will face a substantial risk of unconstitutional policing. This conclusion is supported by the United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division's recently released report (the "DOJ Report"), finding "reasonable cause to believe that [the Maricopa County Sheriffs Office ("MCSO")] engages in a pattern or practice of unconstitutional policing" against Latinos. n32 That nearly three-year investigation documented widespread bias. The DOJ Report found that MCSO "engages in racial profiling of Latinos; unlawfully stops, detains, and arrests Latinos; and unlawfully retaliates against individuals who complain about or criticize MCSO's policies or practices." n33 MCSO targeted people who primarily spoke Spanish or were "dark-skin[ned]." n34 In light of MCSO's behavior, the Department of Homeland Security ("DHS")  \b \i0 \ul0 [*20]\b0 \i0 \ul0   terminated MCSO's authority to assist federal officials in civil immigration violations. n35 In addition, a federal judge recently enjoined MCSO from "detaining any person based solely on knowledge, without more, that the person is in the country without lawful authority" because of allegations of \b \i0 \ul0 [**35]\b0 \i0 \ul0   similar civil rights violations. n36
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n32 See Letter from Thomas E. Perez, Ass't Attorney Gen., Civil Rights Div., U.S. Dep't of Justice, to Bill Montgomery, Maricopa Cnty. Attorney, Arizona (Dec. 15, 2011), http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/spl/documents/mcso_findletter_12-15-11.pdf ("DOJ Report"). The MCSO oversees law enforcement for the most populous section of Arizona, including Phoenix.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n33 \b0 \i \ul0 Id\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 2.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n34 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 8, 11.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n35 Press Release, U.S. Dep't of Homeland Sec, Statement by Secretary Napolitano on DOJ's Findings of Discriminatory Policing in Maricopa County (Dec. 15, 2011), http://www.dhs.gov/ynews/releases/20111215-napolitano-statement-doj-maricopa-county.shtm; Randal C. Archibold, \b0 \i \ul0 Immigration Hard-Liner Has His Wings Clipped,\b0 \i0 \ul0  N.Y. TIMES, Oct. 7, 2009, at A14, http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/07/us/07arizona.html. See also 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1357(g) (The Immigration and Nationality Act, \'a7 \b0 \i \ul0 281(g),\b0 \i0 \ul0  allows the U.S. Attorney General to delegate immigration enforcement functions to specified state and local law enforcement agencies).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**36]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n36 \b0 \i \ul0 Melendres v. Arpaio,\b0 \i0 \ul0  No. CV-07-2513, 2011 WL 6740711-PHX-GMS, slip op. at *22 (D. Ariz. Dec. 23, 2011).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The DOJ Report's findings include racial profiling of Latinos during traffic stops, some of which appear to be pretextual. n37 This conduct likely will increase if police officers are instructed under Section 2 to inquire into immigration status during stops. n38  \b \i0 \ul0 [*21]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Section 2 of S.B. 1070 requires law enforcement to inquire into the immigration status of those an officer has "reasonable suspicion" to suspect are undocumented. n39 However, the statute is silent as to what constitutes a basis for reasonable suspicion. This invites officers to use impermissible proxies such as language or physical characteristics as such basis, despite the statutory language that local and state officers and agencies "may not consider race, color, or national origin in the enforcement of this subsection except to the extent permitted by the United States or Arizona constitution." n40
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n37 DOJ Report, \b0 \i \ul0 supra\b0 \i0 \ul0  note 32, at 6, 18.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**37]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n38 Nor is the danger limited to Maricopa County. Police departments in other Arizona counties, including Cochise County and Pinal County, have also engaged in troubling behavior. See Jim Meyers and Ashley Martella, \b0 \i \ul0 Ariz. Sheriff: Feds Order Release of Illegals to Phony Up Numbers,\b0 \i0 \ul0  NEWSMAX.COM, May 9, 2011, http://www.newsmax.com/Headline/LarryDever-BorderPatrol-Immigration-Arizona/2011/05/06/id/395500 (reporting that Cochise County Sheriff Dever stated that "illegals are committing 'heinous crimes' across America every day," and called "claims that the federal government should be solely responsible for controlling illegal immigration 'balderdash'"); Bill Hess, \b0 \i \ul0 Sheriff Says Feds Being Unrealistic,\b0 \i0 \ul0  WILLCOXRANGENEWS.COM, Feb. 23, 2011, http://www.willcoxrangenews.com/news/article_1643d7c4-3a86-5160-8b4e-5f72489c00c0.html (reporting that Pinal County Sheriff Babeu stated that "the federal government is trying 'to put us in some kind of a trance or brainwash us'").
\par \fs20 \pard 
